017}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2009-2012 || ''[[Balika Vadhu]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/Farida-Jalal-hurt-by-SRK-Karan-Chopra/articleshow/4388383.cms|title=Farida Jalal hurt by SRK-Karan-Chopra - Times of India|website=The Times of India}}</ref> || Badi Masiji  ||\n|-\n| 2010 || ''[[Rishta.com]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/sethshruti/status/9411903789|title=Farida Jalal makes a guest appearance in RISHTA.COM tonight at 8PM on Sony. I hope you'll all be watching :)|first=Shruti|last=Seth|date=February 20, 2010}}</ref> || Ruchika's mother ||\n|-\n| 2011|| ''[[Ammaji Ki Galli]]'' || Ammaji<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.afaqs.com/news/company_briefs/?id=50054_SAB+TV+launches+Ammaji+Ki+Galli|title=SAB TV launches 'Ammaji Ki Galli'|date=June 16, 2011|accessdate=March 14, 2018}}</ref>\n||  \n|-\n| 2013 || ''[[Jeannie Aur Juju]]'' || Duggu Dadi ||\n|-\n| 2014\u20132016 || ''[[Satrangi Sasural]]'' || Gomti Devi Vatsal || \n|}\n\n=== Web Series ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!Year\n!Title\n!Role\n!Platform\n!Notes\n|-\n|2019\n|Parchhayee\n|Ricky's Dadi\n|ZEE5\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/web-series/farida-jalal-parchhayee-zee5-5553836/|title=Farida Jalal: Want to play a negative character but no filmmaker wants to take that risk|date=2019-01-24|website=The Indian Express|language=en-IN|access-date=2019-06-27}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dnaindia.com/entertainment/report-ruskin-bond-s-the-wind-on-haunted-hill-on-zee5-here-s-what-this-ghost-story-is-all-about-2710680|title=Ruskin Bond's 'The Wind On Haunted Hill' on ZEE5: Here's what this ghost story is all about!|date=2019-01-22|website=DNA India|language=en|access-date=2019-06-27}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Farida Jalal}}\n*{{IMDb name|0416077|Farida Jalal}}\n\n{{FilmfareAwardBestSupportingActress 1961-1980}}\n{{FilmfareAwardBestSupportingActress 1981-2000}}\n{{FilmfareCriticsAwardBestActress}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jalal, Farida}}\n[[Category:Actresses in Hindi cinema]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1949 births]]\n[[Category:Indian Muslims]]\n[[Category:Indian film actresses]]\n[[Category:Indian television actresses]]\n[[Category:Indian women television presenters]]\n[[Category:Indian television presenters]]\n[[Category:Actresses from New Delhi]]\n[[Category:Actresses in Tamil cinema]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian actresses]]\n[[Category:21st-century Indian actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses in Telugu cinema]]\n[[Category:Actresses in Hindi television]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Indian actress|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=February 2016}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Farida Jalal\n| image = Farida Jalal.jpg\n| imagesize = \n| caption = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1949|03|14|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[New Delhi]], [[Dominion of India|India]]\n| nationality = [[India]]n\n| occupation = [[Actress]], [[comedian]]\n| years_active = 1967 - present\n| spouse = {{Plainlist |\n*{{marriage|Tabrez Barmavar|1978|2003|reason=died}}\n}}\n| partner = \n| awards = [[Filmfare Best Supporting Actress Award|Best Supporting Actress]]: '''''[[Paras (film)|Paras]]''''' (1972) <br /> [[Filmfare Best Supporting Actress Award|Best Supporting Actress]]: '''''[[Henna]]''''' (1992) <br /> [[Filmfare Critics Award for Best Performance|Best Actress (critics)]]: '''''[[Mammo]]''''' (1995) <br />[[Filmfare Best Supporting Actress Award|Best Supporting Actress]]: '''''[[Dilwale Dulhania Le Jayenge]]''''' (1996)\n| website = \n}}\n\n'''Farida Jalal''' (born 14 March 1949) is an Indian actress. In a film career spanning almost fifty years, Jalal acted in over 200 films in the [[Bollywood|Hindi]], the [[Telugu Cinema|Telugu]], and the [[Tamil Cinema|Tamil]] film industries. Best known for her character driven roles in [[independent film|independent cinema]] and supporting work in mainstream Bollywood productions, Jalal has received such accolades as four [[Filmfare Awards]] and two [[Bengal Film Journalists Association Awards]].\n\nJalal started her career with ''Taqdeer'' (1967). She went on to play leading and supporting roles in numerous motion pictures through the 1970s and early 80s. She is widely remembered for her roles in ''[[Paras (film)|Paras]]'' (1971), ''[[Henna (film)|Henna]]'' (1991) and ''[[Dilwale Dulhania Le Jayenge]]'' (1995), all of which garnered the [[Filmfare Award for Best Supporting Actress]]. She became a household name after portraying motherly roles and strong female characters in the 1990s and the early 2000s. She has also won the [[Filmfare Critics Award for Best Performance]] for her role in ''[[Mammo]]'' (1994). She won the Best Actress Award at the 2012 Harlem International Film Festival for her role in ''[[A Gran Plan]]'' (2012).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/movies/bollywood/story/this-is-what-filmmakers-tell-farida-jalal-on-her-wish-to-play-negative-character-1431190-2019-01-15|title=This is what filmmakers tell Farida Jalal on her wish to play negative character|first1=Indo-Asian News Service|last1=MumbaiJanuary 15|first2=2019UPDATED:|last2=January 15|first3=2019 15:08|last3=Ist|website=India Today}}</ref>\n\nShe has successfully transitioned to numerous shows on [[Indian television]] alongside her work in films. Some of her notable works are the sitcom ''[[Yeh Jo Hai Zindagi]]'', ''[[Dekh Bhai Dekh]]'', ''[[Shararat (TV series)|Shararat]]'' and ''[[Ammaji Ki Galli]]''. She was seen in the soap opera ''[[Satrangi Sasural]]'' on channel [[Zee TV]] portraying the role of Gomti Vatsal a.k.a. Dadi Maa.\n\n== Career ==\nFarida Jalal, who was born on 14 March 1949 in [[New Delhi]] India,<ref name=\"khalid\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thequint.com/entertainment/celebrities/farida-jalal-from-rajesh-khanna-sweetheart-to-dilip-kumar-sister-to-aapa-in-student-of-the-year|title=Happy Birthday Farida Jalal: B-Town's Most Dependable Co-Actor|work=The Quint|last=Mohamed|first=Khalid|accessdate=15 April 2018|date=14 March 2017}}</ref> started her career in the 1960s when she won the United Film Producers Talent Hunt sponsored by [[Filmfare]] in 1965. She, along with [[Rajesh Khanna]] was chosen as finalist and both were presented on stage as winners at the Filmfare Awards function. She got her first film offer for ''Taqdeer'' from [[Tarachand Barjatya]] who happened to be in the audience.<ref name=\"Farida Jalal \u2013 Interview 2000\">[http://cineplot.com/farida-jalal-interview-2000/ Farida Jalal \u2013 Interview (2000)], \"Cineplot.com\"</ref> In an interview in 2014, she said, when asked her about initial part of her career: \"I started my acting career when I was just out of my school St Joseph's Convent in Panchgani, in a film called ''Taqdeer''. I took part in a talent contest and even won. Kaka (Rajesh Khanna) and I were the finalists. How was I to know that I'd soon be doing a film ''Aradhana'' with him?\".<ref name=\"2014 interview\">{{cite news|url=http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/celebrities/features/type/view/id/7616|title=\"I virtually grew up and grew old in the industry\" \u2013 Farida Jalal|last=Ethiraj|first=|date=|work=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nShe usually played the sister or rejected fianc\u00e9e of the male lead, but almost never the female lead. One of her most critically acclaimed roles is in ''[[Bobby (1973 film)|Bobby]]'', where she played the part of the [[mental retardation|mentally challenged]] would-be fianc\u00e9e of [[Rishi Kapoor]]. During the 1980s, her roles progressed from sister and girlfriend to aunt, mother, or grandmother. She is also remembered for her part in ''Aradhana'', in which she plays [[Rajesh Khanna]]'s girlfriend, and sings the song \"Bagon me bahar hai, kaliyon pe nikhar hai\".\n\nWhen asked as to how she started getting typecast as a hero's sister, she quoted in an interview: \"It all started with ''Gopi'' where I was offered the greatest mr Dilip Kumar's sister's role. Forget about refusing, I jumped at the offer. Even if I had the chance to just go and observe him on the set I'd have done it. I love the man. I remember during those days each and every actor was copying Dilip Saab whether it was Dharmendra, Jeetendra or Manoj Kumar. I was much in-demand as Dilip Saab's sister. Every hero wanted the same. Every actor wanted me to play his sister. Sometimes the sister was the film's heroine. The official heroine would just sing her songs, whereas I had all the dramatic scenes. I got my recognition and the awards. In a film called ''Paras'' I was Sanjeev Kumar's sister. But I had a lot more to do than Raakhee-di who played the heroine. I got my first award for it. Then I got my second award for ''Majboor'', a film written by Salimbhai and Javedbhai where Bachchan Saab played my brother. It was so heartening. Why would I want to be heroine when I was getting the stronger parts as the sister?\"<ref name=\"2014 interview\" />\n\nShe acted for over 40 years, only taking a break during 1983 and 1990, when she settled in [[Bangalore]].\n\nDuring the 1990s, Jalal had a part in many major hits in India, among them ''[[Raja Hindustani]]'', ''[[Kuch Kuch Hota Hai]]'', ''[[Dil To Pagal Hai]]'', ''[[Kaho Naa... Pyaar Hai]]'', ''[[Kabhi Khushi Kabhie Gham...]]'' and ''[[Dilwale Dulhania Le Jayenge]]'', for which she won a [[Filmfare Award]] for [[Filmfare Best Supporting Actress Award|Best Supporting Actress]] in 1995. Farida Jalal played the lead in the film ''Mammo''. The film won the National Film Award for Best Feature Film in Hindi. Jalal won the Filmfare Critics Award for Best Performance. She acted in many television serials, such as the hit sitcom ''Dekh Bahi Dekh''.\n\nShe was grandly acclaimed for her role in the 1994 film ''[[Mammo]]'', for which she received the Filmfare Best Performance Award. Earlier, she was also nominated multiple times for 'Best Supporting Actress Award', one for the Amitabh Bachchan-Parveen Babi-Pran starrer ''Majboor'' where she played Amitabh's handicapped sister.\n\nFarida Jalal though, could not get a major break as heroine against any big star except Rajesh Khanna in ''Aaradhana'', but she played the lead role in ''Jeevan Rekha'' in which her husband Tabrez was the hero. Pran and Ajit were also in the film. A song of the film; \"Yaar mere, meri baahon me aaja\" by [[Mohammed Rafi]] from this film had become popular, and is still popular.\n\nJalal starred in ''Shararat (Thoda Jadu, Thodi Nazaakat)'', in which she played a leading role. The comedy is currently airing on the [[Disney Channel]].\n\nIn 2005, she co-hosted the 50th [[Filmfare Awards]] alongside [[Saif Ali Khan]] and [[Sonali Bendre]], in Mumbai. In 2008, she made a special appearance in the [[Punjabi language|Punjabi]] film ''[[Yaariyan (2008 film)|Yaariyan]]''. Recently, she appeared in the soap opera ''[[Balika Vadhu]]''.\n\nIn 2017, she was the victim of a death hoax. On 19 February, rumours did the rounds that she had died.<ref>[http://www.bollywoodlife.com/news-gossip/farida-jalal-on-death-hoax-i-am-happy-to-realise-how-much-people-love-me/] Death rumour</ref> Annoyed, the lady asked her publicist to put the rumours to rest.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://movies.ndtv.com/bollywood/farida-jalal-is-not-dead-internet-stop-spreading-fake-news-please-1661303|title=Farida Jalal Is Not Dead, Internet. 'Stop Spreading Fake News' Please - NDTV Movies|website=NDTVMovies.com}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nJalal was married to actor Tabrez Barmavar, who hails from [[Bhatkal]], [[Karnataka]] and died in September 2003; they have a son named Yaseen. She met her husband on the sets of Jeevan Rekha and fell in love in the course of the film and got married in November 1978. As she was not getting too many film offers after marriage, they moved to Bangalore where her husband had a soap factory business.<ref name=\"Farida Jalal \u2013 Interview 2000\"/> Her son Yaseen is not interested in acting.<ref name=\"2014 interview\" />\n\n== Awards ==\n* 1972: [[Filmfare Best Supporting Actress Award]] for: ''[[Paras (film)|Paras]]'' (1971)\n* 1972:  Bengal Film Journalists Association Award for Best Supporting Actress (Hindi) for: ''Paras'' (1971)\n* 1992:  Filmfare Best Supporting Actress Award for: ''[[Henna (film)|Henna]]'' (1991)\n* 1995: [[Filmfare Critics Award for Best Actress|Filmfare Critics Award for Best Performance]] for: ''[[Mammo]]'' (1994)\n* 1996: [[Bengal Film Journalists Association Awards]] - Best Actress (Hindi), ''Mammo'' (1994)\n* 1996:  Filmfare Best Supporting Actress Award for ''[[Dilwale Dulhania Le Jayenge]]'' (1995)\n* 2012:  Harlem International Film Festival\u2014Best Actress for ''[[A Gran Plan]]''(2012)\n\n== Filmography ==\n=== Film ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- style=\"background:#CCC; text-align:center;\"\n! Year !! Title !! Role !! Notes\n|-\n||1967 ||''Taqdeer''|| Geeta (Youngest daughter of Gopal) || \n|-\n||1968 || [[Baharon Ki Manzil (1968 film)|''Baharon ki Manzil'']] ||  ||\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|1969 || [[Mahal (1969 film)|''Mahal'']] ||  ||\n|-\n| [[Aradhana (1969 film)|''Aradhana'']]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenational.ae/arts-culture/the-best-of-rajesh-khanna-1.382533|title=The best of Rajesh Khanna|website=The National}}</ref> || Renu ||Nominated\u2014Filmfare Award for Best Supporting Actress\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\"|1970 || ''[[Puraskar]]'' || Reshma ||\n|-\n|''[[Naya Raasta]]'' || Radha Pratap Singh ||\n|-\n| ''[[Gopi (1970 film)|Gopi]]'' || Nandini ||\n|-\n| ''[[Devi (1970 film)|Devi]]'' || Shobha ||\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\"|1971||''[[Paras (film)|Paras]]''||Bela Singh||[[Filmfare Best Supporting Actress Award]]<br/> BFJA Awards for Best Supporting Actress (Hindi)\n|-\n| ''[[Khoj (1971 film)|Khoj]]'' || ||\n|-\n| ''[[Amar Prem]]'' || Mrs. Nandkishore Sharma ||\n|-\n| ''[[Pyar Ki Kahani]]'' || Lata ||\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"|1972 || ''[[Zindagi Zindagi]]'' || Shyama ||\n|-\n| ''[[Rivaaj]]'' || ||\n|-\n| ''[[Buniyaad]]'' || ||\n|-\n| rowspan=\"5\"|1973 || [[Heera (film)|''Heera'']] || ||\n|-\n| [[Bobby (1973 film)|''Bobby'']] || Alka Sharma 'Nikki' ||\n|-\n| [[Achanak (1973 film)|''Achanak'']] || Nurse Radha ||\n|-\n| [[Raja Rani (1973 film)|''Raja Rani'']] || Anita || Uncredited\n|-\n| [[Loafer (1973 film)|''Loafer'']]|| Roopa (Gopinath's daughter) ||\n|-\n| rowspan=\"5\"|1974 ||''[[Naya Din Nai Raat]]'' || ||\n|-\n| ''Jeevan Rekha'' || || \n|-\n| [[Majboor (1974 film)|''Majboor'']] || Renu Khanna || Nominated\u2014Filmfare Award for Best Supporting Actress<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rediff.com/movies/slide-show/slide-show-1-raksha-bandhan-special-bollywoods-endearing-bhai-behan-portrayals/20120802.htm|title=Rakhi special: Bollywood's endearing bhai-bahen portrayals|website=Rediff}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Uljhan]]'' || Kamla ||\n|-\n| ''[[Sankalp]]'' || Geeta Sehgal ||\n|-\n| rowspan=\"6\"|1975 || [[Khushboo (1975 film)|''Khushboo'']] || Kusum's friend ||\n|-\n| ''[[Kala Sona]]'' || Bela ||\n|-\n| ''[[Do Jasoos]]'' || Hema Khushalchand ||\n|-\n| ''[[Dhoti Lota Aur Chowpatty]]'' || Rajni ||\n|-\n| ''[[Dharmatma]]'' || Mona ||\n|-\n| ''[[Aakraman]]'' || Asha ||\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\"|1976 || ''[[Shaque]]'' || Mrs. Subramaniam || Nominated\u2014Filmfare Award for Best Supporting Actress\n|-\n| [[Sabse Bada Rupaiya (1976 film)|''Sabse Bada Rupaiya'']] || Bindiya/Shobha ||\n|-\n| ''[[Koi Jeeta Koi Haara]]'' || ||\n|-\n| ''[[Bandalbaaz]]'' || Malti ||\n|-\n| rowspan=\"6\"|1977 || ''[[Kasam Khoon Ki]]'' || Ganga ||\n|-\n| ''[[Alaap]]'' || Sulakshana Gupta ||\n|-\n| ''[[Abhi To Jee Lein]]'' || The Nun ||\n|-\n| ''[[Aakhri Goli]]'' || ||\n|-\n| ''[[Shatranj Ke Khiladi (film)|Shatranj Ke Khiladi]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rediff.com/movies/slide-show/slide-show-1-when-amjad-khan-attenborough-sanjeev-kumar-got-together/20120927.htm|title=Exclusive excerpt from Manik And I, My Life with Satyajit Ray|website=Rediff}}</ref> || Nafisa |